evidence: The microstructure of the CrNb alloy consists of coarse, nearglobular BCC particles and a eutectic mixture of Laves and BCC phases. The average grain size of the matrix is ~200 μm. During HIP at 1400 • C the coarse dendrites transform to near-globular BCC particles.

The ternary CrNbTi alloy was more ductile, but not as strong at 25 • C than the binary CrNb alloy. It exhibited σ y = 1353 MPa, σ p = 1659 MPa (at ε p = 0.042) and fractured at ε f = 0.06 and σ f = 1460 MPa (Fig.  9b ).

The quaternary CrNbTaTi alloy showed excellent malleability at all three temperatures surviving true plastic strain of 0.69 without fracture. However, this was the weakest alloy among the three studied. The yield stress of this alloy was 515 MPa at 25 • C, 62 MPa at 1000 • C and only 20 MPa at 1200 • C.
